const body = `Thanks for the detailed repro — this is a real remaining gap.

A shim already avoids the network when an installed version satisfies the fuzzy request. In this case no installed version matched \`fzf@0.7\`, so remote resolution was necessary; the bug was that failure took far too long.

I have put together fixes for the three delay multipliers:

- DNS resolver failures are now permanent for retry purposes, so mise does not repeat the same failed lookup.
- A hard DNS/connect failure opens a process-local circuit for that network origin. Later requests to the same origin fail immediately instead of paying the timeout again.
- Fast paths using \`prefer_offline\` (including shims, shell activation, and \`mise x\`) now make zero HTTP retries, and remote-version lookups are capped at 3 seconds. Artifact download timeouts are unchanged.

The existing explicit controls remain \`MISE_OFFLINE=1\`, \`MISE_HTTP_RETRIES=0\`, and the HTTP/version-fetch timeout settings, but the shim path should no longer need manual tuning to avoid the ~45s retry cascade.

One nuance in the repro: \`mise x fzf@0.7\` supplies the version as an argument, so it is not identical to config-driven shim selection, but it exercises the same missing-installed-match network path and now receives the same fail-fast HTTP policy.

The changes include regression coverage for DNS classification, the process-local circuit breaker, and retry suppression under \`prefer_offline\`; the full all-features unit suite passes.

*This comment was generated by an AI coding assistant.*`;
